</ul>
</center>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="44" id="mwBXQ"><h3 id="Art">Art</h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt1354" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Main","href":"./Template:Main"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Islamic art"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBXU">Main article: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Islamic_art" title="Islamic art">Islamic art</a></div>
<p id="mwBXY"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Islamic_art" title="Islamic art" id="mwBXc">Islamic art</a> encompasses the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Visual_arts" title="Visual arts" id="mwBXg">visual arts</a> produced from the 7th century onwards by people (not necessarily <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Muslim" title="Muslim" id="mwBXk" class="mw-redirect">Muslim</a>) who lived within the territory that was inhabited by Muslim populations.<sup about="#mwt3264" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-388" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-388"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-388" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 386;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[386]</span></a></sup> It includes fields as varied as architecture, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Calligraphy" title="Calligraphy" id="mwBXo">calligraphy</a>, painting, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Ceramics_(art)" title="Ceramics (art)" id="mwBXs" class="mw-redirect">ceramics</a>, among others.</p>

<p id="mwBXw">While not condemned in the Quran, making images of human beings and animals is frowned on in many Islamic cultures and connected with <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Aniconism_in_Islam" title="Aniconism in Islam" id="mwBX0">laws against idolatry</a> common to all Abrahamic religions, as 'Abdullaah ibn Mas'ood reported that Muhammad said, "Those who will be most severely punished by Allah on the Day of Resurrection will be the image-makers" (reported by al-Bukhaari, see al-Fath, 10/382). However this rule has been interpreted in different ways by different scholars and in different historical periods, and there are examples of paintings of both animals and humans in Mughal, Persian and Turkish art. The existence of this <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Aniconism_in_Islam" title="Aniconism in Islam" id="mwBX4">aversion to creating images of animate beings</a> has been used to explain the prevalence of calligraphy, tessellation and pattern as key aspects of Islamic artistic culture.<sup about="#mwt3234" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-389" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-389"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-389" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 387;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[387]</span></a></sup></p>

<center id="mwBX8">
<ul class="gallery mw-gallery-traditional" typeof="mw:Extension/gallery" about="#mwt2924" data-mw='{"name":"gallery","attrs":{"widths":"240px","heights":"240"},"body":{"extsrc":"\nFile:Planets by ibrahimabutouq.jpg|Islamic calligraphy representing various [[planets]]\nFile:Roof hafez tomb.jpg|Geometric arabesque tiling on the underside of the dome of Hafiz Shirazi&apos;s tomb in [[Shiraz]], [[Iran]]\nFile:Islamic arts museum, KL, Malaysia.jpg|The [[Islamic Arts Museum Malaysia]], the largest museum of [[Islamic arts]] in [[South East Asia]]\n"}}' id="mwBYA">
<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 275px;"><div class="thumb" style="width: 270px; height: 270px;"><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Planets_by_ibrahimabutouq.jpg"><img resource="./File:Planets_by_ibrahimabutouq.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ce/Planets_by_ibrahimabutouq.jpg/240px-Planets_by_ibrahimabutouq.jpg" data-file-width="600" data-file-height="414" data-file-type="bitmap" height="166" width="240" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ce/Planets_by_ibrahimabutouq.jpg/480px-Planets_by_ibrahimabutouq.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ce/Planets_by_ibrahimabutouq.jpg/360px-Planets_by_ibrahimabutouq.jpg 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline></div><div class="gallerytext">Islamic calligraphy representing various <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Planets" title="Planets" class="mw-redirect">planets</a></div></li>
<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 275px;"><div class="thumb" style="width: 270px; height: 270px;"><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Roof_hafez_tomb.jpg"><img resource="./File:Roof_hafez_tomb.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/60/Roof_hafez_tomb.jpg/240px-Roof_hafez_tomb.jpg" data-file-width="3648" data-file-height="2736" data-file-type="bitmap" height="180" width="240" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/60/Roof_hafez_tomb.jpg/480px-Roof_hafez_tomb.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/60/Roof_hafez_tomb.jpg/360px-Roof_hafez_tomb.jpg 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline></div><div class="gallerytext">Geometric arabesque tiling on the underside of the dome of Hafiz Shirazi's tomb in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Shiraz" title="Shiraz">Shiraz</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Iran" title="Iran">Iran</a></div></li>
<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 275px;"><div class="thumb" style="width: 270px; height: 270px;"><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Islamic_arts_museum,_KL,_Malaysia.jpg"><img resource="./File:Islamic_arts_museum,_KL,_Malaysia.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4e/Islamic_arts_museum%2C_KL%2C_Malaysia.jpg/240px-Islamic_arts_museum%2C_KL%2C_Malaysia.jpg" data-file-width="3367" data-file-height="2592" data-file-type="bitmap" height="185" width="240" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4e/Islamic_arts_museum%2C_KL%2C_Malaysia.jpg/480px-Islamic_arts_museum%2C_KL%2C_Malaysia.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4e/Islamic_arts_museum%2C_KL%2C_Malaysia.jpg/360px-Islamic_arts_museum%2C_KL%2C_Malaysia.jpg 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline></div><div class="gallerytext">The <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Islamic_Arts_Museum_Malaysia" title="Islamic Arts Museum Malaysia">Islamic Arts Museum Malaysia</a>, the largest museum of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Islamic_arts" title="Islamic arts" class="mw-redirect">Islamic arts</a> in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./South_East_Asia" title="South East Asia" class="mw-redirect">South East Asia</a></div></li>
</ul>
</center>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="45" id="mwBYE"><h3 id="Music">Music</h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt1360" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Main","href":"./Template:Main"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Islamic music"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBYI">Main article: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Islamic_music" title="Islamic music">Islamic music</a></div>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="46" id="mwBYM"><h3 id="Poetry">Poetry</h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt1361" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Main","href":"./Template:Main"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Islamic poetry"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBYQ">Main article: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Islamic_poetry" title="Islamic poetry">Islamic poetry</a></div>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="47" id="mwBYU"><h3 id="Calendar">Calendar</h3>
<table class="vertical-navbox nowraplinks" style="float:right;clear:right;width:22.0em;margin:0 0 1.0em 1.0em;background:#f9f9f9;border:1px solid #aaa;padding:0.2em;border-spacing:0.4em 0;text-align:center;line-height:1.4em;font-size:88%" about="#mwt1362" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Muslimmonths","href":"./Template:Muslimmonths"},"params":{},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBYY"><tbody><tr><th style="padding:0.2em 0.4em 0.2em;font-size:145%;line-height:1.2em"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Islamic_calendar" title="Islamic calendar">Islamic calendar</a></th></tr><tr><th style="padding:0.1em">
Months</th></tr><tr><td style="padding:0 0.1em 0.4em;text-align:left">
<ol><li><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Muharram" title="Muharram">Muharram</a></li>
<li><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Safar" title="Safar">Safar</a></li>
<li><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Rabi'_al-awwal" title="Rabi' al-awwal">Rabi' al-awwal</a></li>
<li><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Rabi'_al-Thani" title="Rabi' al-Thani">Rabi' al-Thani</a></li>
<li><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Jumada_al-awwal" title="Jumada al-awwal">Jumada al-awwal</a></li>
<li><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Jumada_al-Thani" title="Jumada al-Thani">Jumada al-Thani</a></li>
<li><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Rajab" title="Rajab">Rajab</a></li>
<li><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sha'ban" title="Sha'ban">Sha'ban</a></li>
<li><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Ramadan_(calendar_month)" title="Ramadan (calendar month)">Ramadan</a></li>
<li><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Shawwal" title="Shawwal">Shawwal</a></li>
<li><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Dhu_al-Qidah" title="Dhu al-Qidah">Dhu al-Qidah</a></li>
<li><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Dhu_al-Hijjah" title="Dhu al-Hijjah">Dhu al-Hijjah</a></li></ol></td>
</tr><tr><td style="text-align:right;font-size:115%"><div class="plainlinks hlist navbar mini"><ul><li class="nv-view"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Template:Muslimmonths" title="Template:Muslimmonths"><abbr title="View this template">v</abbr></a></li><li class="nv-talk"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Template_talk:Muslimmonths" title="Template talk:Muslimmonths"><abbr title="Discuss this template">t</abbr></a></li><li class="nv-edit"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Muslimmonths&amp;action=edit"><abbr title="Edit this template">e</abbr></a></li></ul></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt1363" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Main","href":"./Template:Main"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Islamic calendar"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBYc">Main article: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Islamic_calendar" title="Islamic calendar">Islamic calendar</a></div>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwBYg"><a href="./File:Lunar_libration_with_phase_Oct_2007.gif" id="mwBYk"><img resource="./File:Lunar_libration_with_phase_Oct_2007.gif" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/86/Lunar_libration_with_phase_Oct_2007.gif/220px-Lunar_libration_with_phase_Oct_2007.gif" data-file-width="640" data-file-height="642" data-file-type="bitmap" height="221" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/86/Lunar_libration_with_phase_Oct_2007.gif/440px-Lunar_libration_with_phase_Oct_2007.gif 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/86/Lunar_libration_with_phase_Oct_2007.gif/330px-Lunar_libration_with_phase_Oct_2007.gif 1.5x" id="mwBYo"/></a><figcaption id="mwBYs">The phases of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Moon" title="Moon" id="mwBYw">Moon</a> form the basis for the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Islamic_calendar" title="Islamic calendar" id="mwBY0">Islamic calendar</a></figcaption></figure>
<p id="mwBY4">The formal beginning of the Muslim era was chosen, reportedly by <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Umar" title="Umar" id="mwBY8">Caliph Umar</a>, to be the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Hijra_(Islam)" title="Hijra (Islam)" id="mwBZA" class="mw-redirect">Hijra</a> in 622 CE, which was an important turning point in Muhammad's fortunes. It is a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Lunar_calendar" title="Lunar calendar" id="mwBZE">lunar calendar</a> with days lasting from sunset to sunset.<sup about="#mwt1371" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-390" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-390"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-390" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 388;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[388]</span></a></sup> Islamic <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Muslim_holidays" title="Muslim holidays" id="mwBZI" class="mw-redirect">holy days</a> fall on fixed dates of the lunar calendar, which means that they occur in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Seasons" title="Seasons" id="mwBZM" class="mw-redirect">different seasons</a> in different years in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Gregorian_calendar" title="Gregorian calendar" id="mwBZQ">Gregorian calendar</a>. The most important Islamic festivals are <i id="mwBZU"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Eid_al-Fitr" title="Eid al-Fitr" id="mwBZY">Eid al-Fitr</a></i> (<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Arabic_language" title="Arabic language" about="#mwt1366" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"lang-ar","href":"./Template:Lang-ar"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"عيد الفطر"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBZc" class="mw-redirect">Arabic</a><span about="#mwt1366">: </span><span lang="ar" dir="rtl" about="#mwt1366">عيد الفطر</span><span typeof="mw:Entity" about="#mwt1366">‎</span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_containing_Arabic-language_text" about="#mwt1366" id="mwBZg"/>) on the 1st of <i id="mwBZk"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Shawwal" title="Shawwal" id="mwBZo">Shawwal</a></i>, marking the end of the fasting month <i id="mwBZs">Ramadan</i>, and <i id="mwBZw"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Eid_al-Adha" title="Eid al-Adha" id="mwBZ0">Eid al-Adha</a></i> (<span lang="ar" dir="rtl" title="Arabic language text" about="#mwt1367" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"lang","href":"./Template:Lang"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"ar"},"2":{"wt":"عيد الأضحى"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBZ4">عيد الأضحى</span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_containing_Arabic-language_text" about="#mwt1367" id="mwBZ8"/>) on the 10th of <i id="mwBaA"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Dhu_al-Hijjah" title="Dhu al-Hijjah" id="mwBaE">Dhu al-Hijjah</a></i>, coinciding with the end of the Hajj pilgrimage.<sup about="#mwt1429" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-391" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-391"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-391" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 389;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[389]</span></a></sup></p>

<div style="clear:both;" about="#mwt1369" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"-","href":"./Template:-"},"params":{},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBaI"></div>

</section></section><section data-mw-section-id="48" id="mwBaM"><h2 id="Criticism">Criticism</h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt1372" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"main","href":"./Template:Main"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Criticism of Islam"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBaQ">Main article: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Criticism_of_Islam" title="Criticism of Islam">Criticism of Islam</a></div>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwBaU"><a href="./File:Dante_and_Virgil_Meet_Muhammad_and_His_Son-in-law,_Ali_in_Hell.jpg" id="mwBaY"><img resource="./File:Dante_and_Virgil_Meet_Muhammad_and_His_Son-in-law,_Ali_in_Hell.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/Dante_and_Virgil_Meet_Muhammad_and_His_Son-in-law%2C_Ali_in_Hell.jpg/220px-Dante_and_Virgil_Meet_Muhammad_and_His_Son-in-law%2C_Ali_in_Hell.jpg" data-file-width="1200" data-file-height="857" data-file-type="bitmap" height="157" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/Dante_and_Virgil_Meet_Muhammad_and_His_Son-in-law%2C_Ali_in_Hell.jpg/440px-Dante_and_Virgil_Meet_Muhammad_and_His_Son-in-law%2C_Ali_in_Hell.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/Dante_and_Virgil_Meet_Muhammad_and_His_Son-in-law%2C_Ali_in_Hell.jpg/330px-Dante_and_Virgil_Meet_Muhammad_and_His_Son-in-law%2C_Ali_in_Hell.jpg 1.5x" id="mwBac"/></a><figcaption id="mwBag"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./William_Blake" title="William Blake" id="mwBak">William Blake</a>'s illustration of <i id="mwBao"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Inferno_(Dante)" title="Inferno (Dante)" id="mwBas">Inferno</a></i> (19th century) shows Muhammad pulling his chest open which has been sliced by a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Devil_in_Christianity" title="Devil in Christianity" id="mwBaw">devil</a> to symbolize his role as a "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./False_prophet#Christianity" title="False prophet" id="mwBa0">false prophet</a>".<sup about="#mwt1375" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-392" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-392"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-392" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 390;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[390]</span></a></sup></figcaption></figure>
<p id="mwBa4">Criticism of Islam has existed since Islam's formative stages. Early criticism came from Christian authors, many of whom viewed Islam as a Christian <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Heresy" title="Heresy" id="mwBa8">heresy</a> or a form of idolatry and often explained it in apocalyptic terms.<sup about="#mwt3236" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-393" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-393"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-393" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 391;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[391]</span></a></sup> Later there appeared criticism from the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Muslim_world" title="Muslim world" id="mwBbA">Muslim world</a> itself, and also from <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Jewish" title="Jewish" id="mwBbE" class="mw-redirect">Jewish</a> writers and from ecclesiastical Christians.<sup about="#mwt3214" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-WarraqPoetry_394-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"WarraqPoetry"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-WarraqPoetry-394"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-WarraqPoetry-394" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 392;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[392]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt3216" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-Ibn_Kammuna_395-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"Ibn Kammuna"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-Ibn_Kammuna-395"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-Ibn_Kammuna-395" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 393;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[393]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt3218" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-Oussani_396-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"Oussani"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-Oussani-396"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-Oussani-396" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 394;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[394]</span></a></sup> Issues relating to the authenticity and morality of the Quran, the Islamic holy book, are also discussed by critics.<sup about="#mwt1425" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-BibleInQuran_397-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"BibleInQuran"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-BibleInQuran-397"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-BibleInQuran-397" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 395;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[395]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt3220" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-398" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-398"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-398" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 396;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[396]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwBbI">Defamatory images of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Medieval_Christian_views_on_Muhammad" title="Medieval Christian views on Muhammad" id="mwBbM">Muhammad</a>, derived from early 7th century depictions of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./History_of_the_Eastern_Orthodox_Church#Byzantine_period" title="History of the Eastern Orthodox Church" id="mwBbQ">Byzantine Church</a>,<sup about="#mwt3266" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-ReferenceH_399-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"ReferenceH"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-ReferenceH-399"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-ReferenceH-399" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 397;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[397]</span></a></sup> appear in the 14th-century <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Epic_poem" title="Epic poem" id="mwBbU" class="mw-redirect">epic poem</a> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Divine_Comedy" title="Divine Comedy" id="mwBbY">Divine Comedy</a> by <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Dante_Alighieri" title="Dante Alighieri" id="mwBbc">Dante Alighieri</a>. Here, Muhammad appears in the eighth circle of hell, along with Ali. Dante does not blame Islam as a whole, but accuses Muhammad of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Schism" title="Schism" id="mwBbg">schism</a>, by establishing another religion after Christianity.<sup about="#mwt3268" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-400" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-400"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-400" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 398;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[398]</span></a></sup> Dante probably used imageries derived from Islam to describe the layout of hell, despite the negative depictions of its founder.<sup about="#mwt1421" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-ReferenceH_399-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"ReferenceH"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-ReferenceH-399" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 397;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[397]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwBbk"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Apologetic" title="Apologetic" id="mwBbo" class="mw-redirect">Apologetic</a> writings, attributed to <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Abdullah_Ibn_al-Muqaffa" title="Abdullah Ibn al-Muqaffa" id="mwBbs" class="mw-redirect">Abdullah Ibn al-Muqaffa</a>, not only defended <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Manichaeism" title="Manichaeism" id="mwBbw">Manichaeism</a> against Islam, but also critizied the Islamic concept of God. Accordingly, the quranic deity was disregarded as an unjust, tyrannic, irrational and malevolent <i id="mwBb0">demonic entity</i>, who "fights with humans and boasts about His victories" and "sitting on a throne, from which He descends".<sup about="#mwt3270" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-401" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-401"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-401" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 399;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[399]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt3272" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-402" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-402"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-402" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 400;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[400]</span></a></sup> Such anthropomorphic characteristics were also repudiated by Manichaeans.<sup about="#mwt3274" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-403" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-403"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-403" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 401;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[401]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwBb4">Other criticisms focus on the question of human rights in modern Muslim-majority countries, and the treatment of women in Islamic law and practice.<sup about="#mwt3222" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-women_404-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"women"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-women-404"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-women-404" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 402;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[402]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt3224" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-IslamInEurope_405-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"IslamInEurope"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-IslamInEurope-405"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-IslamInEurope-405" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 403;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[403]</span></a></sup> In wake of the recent <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Multiculturalism" title="Multiculturalism" id="mwBb8">multiculturalism</a> trend, Islam's influence on the ability of Muslim immigrants in the West to assimilate has been <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Criticism_of_multiculturalism" title="Criticism of multiculturalism" id="mwBcA">criticized</a>.<sup about="#mwt3226" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-Modood_406-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"Modood"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-Modood-406"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-Modood-406" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 404;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[404]</span></a></sup> Both in his public and personal life, others objected the moralitiy of Muhammad, therefore also the sunnah as a rolemodel.<sup about="#mwt1448" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-Oussani_396-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"Oussani"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-Oussani-396" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 394;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[394]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt3228" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-WarraqQuest_407-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"WarraqQuest"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-WarraqQuest-407"}}'><a href="./Islam#cite_note-WarraqQuest-407" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 405;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[405]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="49" id="mwBcE"><h2 id="See_also">See also</h2>
