Encyclopedia+of+Islam&amp;rft.pages=34&amp;rft.pub=Infobase+Publishing&amp;rft.date=2009&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-4381-2696-8&amp;rft.aulast=Campo&amp;rft.aufirst=Juan+Eduardo&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DOZbyz_Hr-eIC&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AIslam" class="Z3988" about="#mwt29" id="mwBjk"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt29" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwBjo"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-9" id="cite_note-9"><a href="./Islam#cite_ref-9" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-9" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation encyclopaedia" about="#mwt30" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite encyclopedia","href":"./Template:Cite_encyclopedia"},"params":{"author":{"wt":"İbrahim Özdemir"},"title":{"wt":"Environment"},"editor":{"wt":"Ibrahim Kalin"},"encyclopedia":{"wt":"The Oxford Encyclopedia of Philosophy, Science, and Technology in Islam"},"publisher":{"wt":"Oxford University Press"},"location":{"wt":"Oxford"},"year":{"wt":"2014"},"subscription":{"wt":"yes"},"quote":{"wt":"When Meccan pagans demanded proofs, signs, or miracles for the existence of God, the Qurʾān&apos;s response was to direct their gaze at nature&apos;s complexity, regularity, and order. The early verses of the Qurʾān, therefore, reveal an invitation to examine and investigate the heavens and the earth, and everything that can be seen in the environment [...] The Qurʾān thus makes it clear that everything in Creation is a miraculous sign of God (āyah), inviting human beings to contemplate the Creator."},"doi":{"wt":"10.1093/acref:oiso/9780199812578.001.0001/acref-9780199812578-e-237"},"doi-broken-date":{"wt":"2018-09-08"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBjs">İbrahim Özdemir (2014). "Environment".  In Ibrahim Kalin. <i id="mwBjw">The Oxford Encyclopedia of Philosophy, Science, and Technology in Islam</i>. Oxford: Oxford University Press. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier" id="mwBj0">doi</a>:<a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="//doi.org/10.1093%2Facref%3Aoiso%2F9780199812578.001.0001%2Facref-9780199812578-e-237" id="mwBj4">10.1093/acref:oiso/9780199812578.001.0001/acref-9780199812578-e-237</a> (inactive 2018-09-08). <span class="cs1-subscription" id="mwBj8">(Subscription required (<span title="The site requires a paid subscription to access this page." id="mwBkA">help</span>))</span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Pages_containing_links_to_subscription-only_content" id="mwBkE"/>. <q id="mwBkI">When Meccan pagans demanded proofs, signs, or miracles for the existence of God, the Qurʾān's response was to direct their gaze at nature's complexity, regularity, and order. The early verses of the Qurʾān, therefore, reveal an invitation to examine and investigate the heavens and the earth, and everything that can be seen in the environment [...] The Qurʾān thus makes it clear that everything in Creation is a miraculous sign of God (āyah), inviting human beings to contemplate the Creator.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Environment&amp;rft.btitle=The+Oxford+Encyclopedia+of+Philosophy%2C+Science%2C+and+Technology+in+Islam&amp;rft.place=Oxford&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2014&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1093%2Facref%3Aoiso%2F9780199812578.001.0001%2Facref-9780199812578-e-237&amp;rft.au=%C4%B0brahim+%C3%96zdemir&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AIslam" class="Z3988" about="#mwt30" id="mwBkM"></span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Pages_with_DOIs_inactive_since_2018" about="#mwt30" id="mwBkQ"/><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt30" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwBkU"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-People-of-the-Book-10" id="cite_note-People-of-the-Book-10"><a href="./Islam#cite_ref-People-of-the-Book_10-0" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-People-of-the-Book-10" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation web" about="#mwt48" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite web","href":"./Template:Cite_web"},"params":{"url":{"wt":"https://www.pbs.org/empires/islam/faithpeople.html"},"title":{"wt":"People of the Book"},"website":{"wt":"[[Islam: Empire of Faith]]"},"publisher":{"wt":"PBS"},"accessdate":{"wt":"2010-12-18"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBkY"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://www.pbs.org/empires/islam/faithpeople.html" id="mwBkc">"People of the Book"</a>. <i id="mwBkg"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Islam:_Empire_of_Faith" title="Islam: Empire of Faith" id="mwBkk">Islam: Empire of Faith</a></i>. PBS<span class="reference-accessdate" id="mwBko">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap" id="mwBks">2010-12-18</span></span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Islam%3A+Empire+of+Faith&amp;rft.atitle=People+of+the+Book&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pbs.org%2Fempires%2Fislam%2Ffaithpeople.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AIslam" class="Z3988" about="#mwt48" id="mwBkw"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt48" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwBk0"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-11" id="cite_note-11"><a href="./Islam#cite_ref-11" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-11" class="mw-reference-text">Reeves, J.C. (2004). <i id="mwBk4">Bible and Qurʼān: Essays in scriptural intertextuality</i>. Leiden [u.a.: Brill. p. 177</span></li><li about="#cite_note-12" id="cite_note-12"><a href="./Islam#cite_ref-12" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-12" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation news" about="#mwt49" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Cite news","href":"./Template:Cite_news"},"params":{"url":{"wt":"http://www.cnn.com/2015/10/21/living/yom-kippur-muslims/index.html"},"title":{"wt":"Why Muslims celebrate a Jewish holiday"},"last":{"wt":"Moghul"},"first":{"wt":"Haroon"},"publisher":{"wt":"CNN"},"access-date":{"wt":"2018-01-18"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBk8">Moghul, Haroon. <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://www.cnn.com/2015/10/21/living/yom-kippur-muslims/index.html" id="mwBlA">"Why Muslims celebrate a Jewish holiday"</a>. CNN<span class="reference-accessdate" id="mwBlE">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap" id="mwBlI">2018-01-18</span></span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Why+Muslims+celebrate+a+Jewish+holiday&amp;rft.aulast=Moghul&amp;rft.aufirst=Haroon&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.cnn.com%2F2015%2F10%2F21%2Fliving%2Fyom-kippur-muslims%2Findex.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AIslam" class="Z3988" about="#mwt49" id="mwBlM"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt49" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwBlQ"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-13" id="cite_note-13"><a href="./Islam#cite_ref-13" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span 