itics</i>. Oxford University Press.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Shar%C4%AB%CA%BFah&amp;rft.btitle=The+Oxford+Encyclopedia+of+Islam+and+Politics&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2014&amp;rft.aulast=Vik%C3%B8r&amp;rft.aufirst=Knut+S.&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fbridgingcultures.neh.gov%2Fmuslimjourneys%2Fitems%2Fshow%2F226&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AIslam" class="Z3988" about="#mwt423" id="mwCeE"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt423" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwCeI"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-Esposito,_John_2001-126" id="cite_note-Esposito,_John_2001-126"><a href="./Islam#cite_ref-Esposito,_John_2001_126-0" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-Esposito,_John_2001-126" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt434" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"first1":{"wt":"John L."},"last1":{"wt":"Esposito"},"authorlink1":{"wt":"John Esposito"},"first2":{"wt":"Natana J."},"last2":{"wt":"DeLong-Bas"},"authorlink2":{"wt":"Natana J. DeLong-Bas"},"title":{"wt":"Women in Muslim Family Law"},"url":{"wt":"{{google books|plainurl=y|id=MOmaDq8HKCgC|page=2}}"},"year":{"wt":"2001"},"publisher":{"wt":"Syracuse University Press"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-0-8156-2908-5"},"pages":{"wt":"2–"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwCeM"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./John_Esposito" title="John Esposito" id="mwCeQ">Esposito, John L.</a>; <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Natana_J._DeLong-Bas" title="Natana J. DeLong-Bas" id="mwCeU">DeLong-Bas, Natana J.</a> (2001). <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=MOmaDq8HKCgC&amp;pg=PA2" id="mwCeY"><i id="mwCec">Women in Muslim Family Law</i></a>. Syracuse University Press. pp.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCeg"> </span>2–. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwCek">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCeo"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-8156-2908-5" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-8156-2908-5" id="mwCes">978-0-8156-2908-5</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Women+in+Muslim+Family+Law&amp;rft.pages=2-&amp;rft.pub=Syracuse+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2001&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-8156-2908-5&amp;rft.aulast=Esposito&amp;rft.aufirst=John+L.&amp;rft.au=DeLong-Bas%2C+Natana+J.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DMOmaDq8HKCgC%26pg%3DPA2&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AIslam" class="Z3988" about="#mwt434" id="mwCew"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt434" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwCe0"/> Quote: "[...], by the ninth century, the classical theory of law fixed the sources of Islamic law at four: the <i id="mwCe4">Quran</i>, the <i id="mwCe8">Sunnah</i> of the Prophet, <i id="mwCfA">qiyas</i> (analogical reasoning), and <i id="mwCfE">ijma</i> (consensus)."</span></li><li about="#cite_note-127" id="cite_note-127"><a href="./Islam#cite_ref-127" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-127" class="mw-reference-text">Ashk Dahlen <i id="mwCfI">Islamic Law, Epistemology and Modernity: Legal Philosophy in Contemporary Iran</i> Routledge 2004 <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt456" typeof="mw:Exte